text=:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts%0a:Expansion: Maybe it's not as bad for new Japanese speakers as it seems!%0a:Author: TimG%0a:Original: [[Articles.ToneInEnglishAndJapanese|ToneInEnglishAndJapanese]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.brandonf|brandonf]]%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 24.02.2021 - 19:59%0a:Status: ungraded%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI came across a blog post that made an interesting argument about Japanese pitch accents: Pitch accents a major factor in becoming conversationally fluent in the language. Here's the blog post: https://www.lucalampariello.com/japanese-pitch-accent/%0a%0aNow, he doesn't say that it isn't important to the language. To the contrary, he says that anyone seeking to become truly fluent must study it in order to sound natural. His point was geared more towards beginners, to whom he notes that Japanese people will understand what you are saying without you using a pitch accent (and even if you use the wrong accent you will probably still be understood, you will just sound foreign). His second point speaks to your last paragraph, in which he says that different accents have different pitch accents, so Japanese people are used to many different pitch accents on words (at least to some extent).%0a%0aI found this very interesting, because it makes the progression for learning Japanese a little bit clearer. Of course, you shouldn't neglect this completely, but it can be learned after one is comfortable with formality rules and sentence structure (etc.)%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a#foxbegin 210512-000938-915580#%0a!!Backup interface%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a#foxend 210512-000938-915580#
